page.title: 09NATURAL HISTORY
page.content: Many natural habitats provide an abun- dance of wild life in this region. The River Humber, with large mudflats,sup- ports a variety of bird life. Wading birds are attracted to the feeding grounds at low water red-shanks, green shanks, curlews,shell ducks, mallards, teal, wigeon, cormorants and an occas- ional heron are just some of the species to be found. Reeds Island is a haven for wildlife. Thousands of gulls roost there and on surrounding mud banks. The island is a nesting place for long eared owls and red deer have been introduced onto the grassland.Oc- casionally a seal can be seen basking in the river.In Autumn pink foot, grey lag and Canada geese feed on the mud- banks on their migration south. Oil polution in the river can severely affect the bird population. There is an abundance of small mammals.
